Here's an example of how you could structure these collection classes to work with your existing rendering system:

```cpp
class PointCollection : public IDrawable {
public:
    PointCollection() = default;
    // Optional: Add constructor that takes an initializer list of Points

    void AddPoint(const Point& point) {
        points.push_back(point);
    }

    void Render(Renderer& renderer) const override {
        // Loop through the points and call render on each one
        for (const auto& point : points) {
            point.Render(renderer);
        }
    }

private:
    std::vector<Point> points;
};
```

Similarly, you can create `LineCollection`, `RectCollection`, and other such collection classes that implement the `IDrawable` interface and encapsulate a collection of shapes.

Each shape class, like `Point`, `LineSegment`, and `Rectangle`, implements its own `Render` method, which uses SDL functions directly to render itself.

When it's time to render a collection of points or lines, you would create a `PointCollection` or `LineCollection` object, add the primitives to it, and then use your `Renderer::Render` method to render the collection:

```cpp
PointCollection pointCollection;
// ... add points to the collection
Renderer renderer;
renderer.Render(pointCollection, myColor);
```

The advantages of this approach are:

- It employs the Composite Pattern, allowing you to treat individual objects and compositions of objects uniformly.
- It aligns with your goal of decentralizing the `Renderer`.
- It avoids bloating the singular object classes with responsibilities for collections.

However, one trade-off is that rendering collections of primitives one by one rather than in batch could be less efficient, especially if you have a very large number of primitives. If performance becomes an issue, you might optimize this later on by introducing batching capability into your collection classes that directly leverage SDL's batch drawing functions (`SDL_RenderDrawPoints`, `SDL_RenderDrawLines`, etc.) under the hood.

Since you aren't planning to expose the SDL backend to users, you would call SDL functions from within these `Render` methods, ensuring the users are not aware of the SDL-specific implementation. This gives you a nice balance between clean abstraction and performance.
